---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="L. reuteri ATCC PTA 6475, Oxytocin & the Gut–Brain Axis | Yoghurt of Youth"
  description="The research behind LVLV — L. reuteri ATCC PTA 6475, a strain studied for its antipathogenic activity and its connection to oxytocin and the gut–brain axis. Educational guide."
>
  <section
    id="lvlv"
    class="relative scroll-mt-32 md:scroll-mt-24 bg-white text-slate-800 py-12"
  >
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-8">
      <h1 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900">
        LVLV: <em>L. reuteri</em> ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475 &amp; the Gut–Brain Axis
      </h1>

      <p class="mt-4 text-slate-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong>LVLV</strong> is the finishing variant in our three-week rotation,
        fermented with live <em>Lactobacillus reuteri</em> ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475.
        It is one of the most extensively researched <em>L. reuteri</em> strains,
        studied both for its antipathogenic activity and, intriguingly, for its
        relationship with the <em>gut–brain axis</em>, including pathways involving
        the hormone oxytocin. This page is an educational overview of what that
        research describes.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">
        The strain: ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475 is an <em>L. reuteri</em> strain originally isolated
        from human breast milk. Like our other strains, it has been studied for its
        antipathogenic properties, its capacity to coexist with beneficial flora
        while limiting less-welcome microbes. In laboratory studies it has shown a
        notable ability to adhere to the gut lining, an area researchers have
        explored in connection with its broader effects.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">
        What is the gut–brain axis?
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        The <strong>gut–brain axis</strong> is the term researchers use for the
        two-way communication between the gut and the nervous system. It is one of
        the most active areas of microbiome science: studies have explored how the
        microbes living in our gut may influence signalling that reaches the brain,
        and how the brain in turn influences the gut. It is the framework through
        which scientists investigate the links between gut health and mood, stress,
        and wellbeing.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">
        ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475 and oxytocin: what the research explores
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong>Oxytocin</strong> is a naturally occurring hormone involved in
        social bonding, calm, and wellbeing, sometimes informally called the
        "love hormone." A body of research has investigated whether
        ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475 influences oxytocin pathways. In a series of
        well-known animal studies, this strain was observed to up-regulate oxytocin
        and produce a range of downstream effects in mice and rats, from faster
        wound healing to changes in social behaviour and maternal care.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        It is important to be clear about what this research is and is not. Most of
        the oxytocin findings to date come from <em>animal models</em>, and the
        mechanisms in humans are still being studied. This is a genuine and
        fascinating area of <em>scientific investigation</em>, described in published
        literature, not a claim that this yoghurt will affect your mood, hormones,
        or health. We share it because it is the research that inspired LVLV, and
        because it is a question our customers often ask about.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">
        Why we call it the "finishing" variant
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Our three strains have each been researched for complementary roles.
        <strong>PRCXN</strong> (DSM&nbsp;17648) is studied in connection with
        <em>Helicobacter pylori</em> in the stomach; <strong>SPCTRL</strong>
        (DSM&nbsp;17938) is studied for supporting microbial balance further down
        the gut. <strong>LVLV</strong> (ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475) is the strain most
        associated with the gut–brain axis in research.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        We think of LVLV as the <em>finishing</em> note in the rotation: where the
        first two strains are researched for restoring and balancing the gut
        environment, LVLV is the one studied in connection with the gut–brain
        conversation that sits on top of it. Together, the three are intended to be
        enjoyed in rotation as part of a varied, gut-focused routine.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">
        How this relates to our yoghurt
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        LVLV is one of the three <em>L. reuteri</em> yoghurts we ferment, each at
        live counts of <strong>over 100 billion CFU</strong> per 250&nbsp;ml
        bottle, lactose-free and with no added sweeteners. You can read about all
        three strains on our
        <a href="/about" class="underline hover:text-amber-500 transition">about page</a>,
        or browse the yoghurt in our
        <a href="/shop" class="underline hover:text-amber-%00 transition">shop</a>.
      </p>

      <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900">Selected research</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700 text-sm">
        Independent research relating to <em>L. reuteri</em> ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475:
      </p>
      <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 mt-2 space-y-1 text-sm text-slate-700">
        <li>
          <span class="font-medium">Poutahidis et&nbsp;al., 2013 (PLOS ONE):</span>
          &nbsp;<em>L. reuteri</em> ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475 was observed to up-regulate
          oxytocin and accelerate wound healing in mice, a finding researchers have
          linked to gut–brain signalling.
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="font-medium">Li et&nbsp;al., 2022 (npj Biofilms and Microbiomes):</span>
          &nbsp;a one-year randomised human trial found <em>L. reuteri</em>
          ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475 supplementation supported gut microbiota richness
          and inflammatory status in older women.
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="font-medium">Frontiers in Gastroenterology, 2023:</span>
          &nbsp;a trial combining ATCC&nbsp;PTA&nbsp;6475 and DSM&nbsp;17938 for IBS
          noted the former's role in gut–brain signalling pathways.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="mt-4 text-slate-600 text-xs leading-relaxed">
        <strong>Important:</strong> this page is educational information only. It is
        not medical advice, and it is not a claim that our yoghurt treats, cures, or
        prevents any condition, or that it affects mood, hormones, or health. Much of
        the research described is at an early or animal-model stage. Our products are
        fermented foods intended to be enjoyed as part of a healthy lifestyle. Original
        publications are available via PubMed and other open scientific databases. If
        you are exploring your own gut health, we'd encourage reading primary sources
        and speaking with a qualified healthcare professional.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>